Q1:- What is sealed classes in java. ?
Ans: Sealed is a keyword in java, Which was introduced in java 17 that restrict the classes to exteds or implements.
     It control the inheritance hierarchy.

Example:
        public sealed class A permits B,C{}

      final class B extends A{} // Its allowed to extends because its permitted by class A.
      class C extends A{}       // Error: The class that extends any sealed class that should be final,sealed or non-sealed.

   public sealed interface I1 permits B,C{}

  final class A implements I1 {}  // Its fine.
  final interface I2 exteds I2{}  // Not Allowed because interface could not be final. So for interface we use sealed or non-sealed.

sealed Classes or Interface are used to Prevents unwanted or accidental subclassing.

